# **Chapter 16 — Control and Dependence**

**1941–1953 CE**

The system has regained control.

But it does not control its environment.

Internal centralization has been effective.
The state functions.
The structure responds.
Authority exists.

But the context has changed.

And that context redefines everything.

The Second World War is not a distant event.
It is a structural force that cuts through the system.

Iran is not the center of the conflict.
But it is a strategic point.

That is the problem.

When a system occupies a critical position,
it ceases to be ignored.

And when it cannot fully defend that position,
it is intervened upon.

1941.

External forces enter Iranian territory.

Not to destroy the system.
To secure interests.

The center does not collapse due to internal weakness.
It is displaced by external pressure.

Reza Shah is forced to abdicate.

The system does not disappear.
It adjusts.

But the adjustment is not autonomous.

It is conditioned.

That is the shift.

The system has managed to reconstruct its internal coherence.
But it has not fully regained its independence.

Here, the key concept of this stage emerges.

Limited autonomy.

The system functions.
But within margins defined by others.

This deeply alters its behavior.

Decisions no longer respond solely to internal logic.
They respond to external balance.

To broader interests.
To global dynamics.

Another tension appears here.

The system must maintain internal control.
But it must also avoid direct external confrontation.

That balance is not stable.

It is unstable by definition.

And when a system operates under unstable equilibrium,
any event can amplify its tensions.

That event occurs.

1953.

An attempt to redefine the relationship
with the external environment
triggers a direct response.

Intervention.
Reconfiguration of power.

The system does not lose its form.
But its direction is once again influenced from outside.

That is the point.

The system is not internally weak.
But it is not fully sovereign externally.

As Mark J. Gasiorowski notes,
the 1953 intervention reflected the ability of external powers
to directly influence Iran’s political structure
within the context of the Cold War.¹

This is fundamental.

The system has learned to rebuild.
To centralize.
To operate with internal coherence.

But it has not yet resolved
its relationship with the global environment.

And that relationship defines its limits.

Here, the system enters a new phase.

Not of reconstruction.
Not of fragmentation.

Of forced equilibrium.

It must sustain itself internally
while adjusting externally.

That equilibrium does not eliminate tensions.

It contains them.

And it does so for a time.

But all contained tension
tends to accumulate.

That is the transition point.

The system functions.
But under constant pressure.

And when pressure is constant,
the system does not collapse immediately.

It prepares to do so.

---

¹ Gasiorowski, Mark J. *U.S. Foreign Policy and the Shah: Building a Client State in Iran*. Ithaca: Cornell University Press, 1991.

